※※
# clone-sky-workflow

Manually-run workflow that duplicates an existing `.sky` as a new template under a new
name — and crucially NEUTRALIZES the copy's trigger so the two never double-fire. Pure
bash for the copy + rewrite; one small claude lint-fix loop to land it clean.

Why neutralize the trigger? A naive `cp a.sky b.sky` copies the trigger block verbatim.
If the source fires on, say, `trigger.github.events = ["issues"]`, the clone now fires on
the SAME event — so one GitHub issue starts TWO runs (silent duplicate work + double
spend). Stripping every `trigger.*` line makes the clone manual by default (no trigger
block == manual), which is what a fresh template should be. That strip is the whole point.

  (manual run: --var dir, name, new-name)
       │
       ▼
   ┌────────┐  source missing ──▶ list <dir> + exit 1
   │  copy  │  dest exists     ──▶ exit 1 (never clobber)
   └────────┘  else: cp source -> dest
       │
       ▼
   ┌─────────┐  in dest: name = "<old>" -> name = "<new>" (temp-file sed)
   │ rewrite │  then delete every `^trigger.` line -> clone is manual
   └─────────┘
       │
       ▼
   ┌────────┐ ⟲  loop.until.bash: sky lint dest  (max 6 passes)
   │  lint  │     sonnet + sky-workflow-authoring fixes any leftover issue
   └────────┘
       │
       ▼
   ┌──────────┐  sky describe dest (best-effort) + "done"
   │ describe │
   └──────────┘

Run it (state where the source lives with --var dir):

  sky run clone-sky-workflow \
    --var dir=".sky/workflows" \
    --var name="source-name" \
    --var new-name="clone-name"

  - dir       directory both files live in — STATE THIS (e.g. .sky/workflows)
  - name      existing kebab-case filename to clone (no .sky extension)
  - new-name  new kebab-case filename + workflow name for the clone (no .sky extension)

Note on the trigger strip: it deletes any line beginning with `trigger.` (github / cron /
schedule / sky_event / manual). With no trigger block the workflow is manual by default.
The lint loop then repairs anything the strip left dangling (e.g. a now-orphaned
`secrets`/`when` reference) so the clone ships clean.
※※

⊕meta⊕
name = "clone-sky-workflow"
description = "Duplicate a .sky as a new manual template under a new name, neutralizing the copied trigger so both never double-fire, then lint clean. Fire via: sky run clone-sky-workflow --var dir=<dir> --var name=<source> --var new-name=<clone>"
trigger.manual = true
output_style = "terse"
max_budget_usd = 2.00
⊕⊕

※※
Step 1 — copy. Resolves the source, refuses if it is missing (lists the dir to help) and
refuses if the destination already exists (never clobber an existing workflow). On success
it plain-copies source -> dest. No mutation of either file's contents yet.
※※

§copy§
bash = "set -e\nSRC=\"$SKY_DIR/$SKY_NAME.sky\"\nDST=\"$SKY_DIR/$SKY_NEW_NAME.sky\"\nif [ ! -f \"$SRC\" ]; then echo \"[clone] no source workflow at $SRC\"; echo \"[clone] available in $SKY_DIR:\"; ls \"$SKY_DIR\" 2>/dev/null || true; exit 1; fi\nif [ -e \"$DST\" ]; then echo \"[clone] destination already exists: $DST\"; exit 1; fi\ncp \"$SRC\" \"$DST\"\necho \"[clone] copied $SKY_NAME -> $SKY_NEW_NAME\""
§§

※※
Step 2 — rewrite. Two edits to the destination, both via portable temp-file sed (no
`sed -i`; BSD and GNU differ). First retarget the meta name to the new name. Then strip
every `^trigger.` line with `grep -v` to a temp file and `mv` it back — this is the
neutralization that stops the clone double-firing. With no trigger block the clone is
manual by default.
※※

§rewrite§
depends_on = ["copy"]
bash = "set -e\nDST=\"$SKY_DIR/$SKY_NEW_NAME.sky\"\nsed \"s/^name = \\\"$SKY_NAME\\\"/name = \\\"$SKY_NEW_NAME\\\"/\" \"$DST\" > \"$DST.tmp\" && mv \"$DST.tmp\" \"$DST\"\ngrep -v '^trigger\\.' \"$DST\" > \"$DST.tmp\" && mv \"$DST.tmp\" \"$DST\"\nstripped=$(grep -c '^trigger\\.' \"$DST\" 2>/dev/null || echo 0)\necho \"[clone] set name -> $SKY_NEW_NAME and neutralized trigger (remaining trigger lines: $stripped)\""
§§

※※
Step 3 — lint. A loop node: each pass reads the clone fresh, runs `sky lint`, and fixes
every reported issue (e.g. an orphaned secrets/when reference left by the trigger strip).
The loop.until.bash re-runs the node until lint exits 0 (max 6 passes). Loop nodes can't
chain a session, so the prompt re-reads the file each pass.
※※

§lint§
model = "sonnet"
depends_on = ["rewrite"]
skills = ["sky-workflow-authoring"]
loop.until.bash = "sky lint \"$SKY_DIR/$SKY_NEW_NAME.sky\""
loop.max = 6
§§

∆lint∆
Read {{dir}}/{{new-name}}.sky, then run `sky lint {{dir}}/{{new-name}}.sky` and read its output. Fix every reported error and warning in that file, using the sky-workflow-authoring skill's SKY-WF-* code table to map each code to its fix. Context: this file is a clone of another workflow with its trigger lines stripped, so it is now a manual workflow — do NOT add a trigger back. Likely leftovers from the strip: a `when`/`secrets`/`mcp_servers` reference that pointed at trigger payload data, or a `name` mismatch. Ensure `name = "{{new-name}}"` matches the filename. Keep the workflow body in English. Re-run lint after editing. This node loops until lint exits 0 — make concrete fixes each pass. When clean, output the final lint result and the file path.
∆∆

※※
Step 4 — describe. Best-effort `sky describe` of the finished clone for a quick
human-readable summary (tolerated if the subcommand is unavailable), then prints done.
※※

§describe§
depends_on = ["lint"]
bash = "DST=\"$SKY_DIR/$SKY_NEW_NAME.sky\"\nsky describe \"$DST\" 2>/dev/null || true\necho \"[clone] done -> $DST\""
§§
